					<marginalia_text>
						<!-- Continued from facing page, in text, Ha2.134v --> [[F6v]: Corduba adolescentulus vtroq[ue] erat egregius: et arguta
						ratiocinatione pra[e] ca[e]teris: et multiplici artiu[m] instructu super omnes. Proximus illi Fortius. Fortio Ramus:
						Ramo Freigius: Freigio Gregoris: Gregorio =]
						= Caius Julius Guercentius, qui sexcentis audientibus
						profitebatur, se quindecim
						diebus mathematicas scientias perfecta explicatione
					</marginalia_text>
                    <!-- CG: I'm unsure who this is. --> <!--JG: Can't find anything either. Will ask specialist-->
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						pra[e]lecturum: Geometr. Arithm. Astron.
						( Egregius mea memoria professor, et discursor
						in pla[e]risq[ue] admirabilis: idemq[ue]
						) imberbis adolescens,
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						et pra[e]lector
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						gladiatus. Post triduu[m], à Lauherno in philosophia;
						à Brouno in Mathematicis lacessitus: magis
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Richard Laugherne"/>
					<person name="Lancelot Brown"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
					<marginalia_text>
						( speciosè, quàm energeticè.
						Lauhernu[m], impudentem scurram, et
						egregium nebulonem sa[e]pè appellabat. Fugit metus causâ.
					</marginalia_text>					
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				[[F6v]: A very young man in Corduba was excellent in both disciplines;
				and with clever reasoning, he was beyond the other men; and instructed by various men 
				of the arts, he was above all men. Fortius was next to him, and Ramus next Fortius.
				Next to Ramus was Freigius, and next to Freigius Gregoire. Next to Gregoire] Caius Julius Guercentius, who declared to six hundred listeners,
				that he was going to give a complete explanation of the mathematical
				sciences in just fifteen days, including geometry, arithmetic, and astronomy.
				In my memory, he is an illustrious professor, and a wondrous discourser 
				on many subjects; at the same time, he was a beardless youth and an armed lecturer. <!-- CG: 'gladiatus' is perplexing. --> <!--JG: I don't get this either. Will ask specialist, maybe it's an expression we don't know of-->
				After three days, he was provoked by Laugherne in philosophy and by Brown in mathematics,
				however they were more showy than effective.
				He frequently called Laugherne an impudent dandy and a singular scoundrel, who then fled in fear.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
